	anonymous class :
		An anonymous class in Java is a nameless inner class defined and instantiated in a single 				expression, usually used to override methods or implement interfaces on the spot.
		
	Functional Interface (Inbuilt) = can implement using anonymous class: (we can pass and return any data-type)
		Consumer<Integer> => function accepts something and does not return anything   : accept(int n)
		Function<Integer, Integer> => function accepts something and returns something : apply(int n) return x;
		Predicate<Integer> => function accepts something and returns always Boolean    : test(int n) return t/f;
		Supplier<Integer> => function does not accept anything and returns something   : get() return x;
		UnaryOperator<Integer> => function accepts 1 input and return same type output : apply(int n)
		BinaryOperator<Integer> => function accepts 2 input and return same type output: apply(int i, int j)

		Consumer - 1 perameter
